  {
    "name": "Humerus",
    "type": "Long Bone",
    "region": "Arm",
    "image": "",
    "overview": "The humerus is the longest and largest bone of the upper limb. It articulates proximally with the glenoid cavity of the scapula at the shoulder joint and distally with the radius and ulna at the elbow joint.",
    "features": "Proximal end: head, anatomical neck, greater and lesser tubercles, intertubercular sulcus. Shaft: deltoid tuberosity, radial groove. Distal end: medial and lateral epicondyles, capitulum, trochlea, olecranon fossa.",
    "attachments": "Rotator cuff muscles (supraspinatus, infraspinatus, teres minor and subscapularis) attach to the tubercles. Pectoralis major, latissimus dorsi and teres major attach to the intertubercular groove. Deltoid inserts on the deltoid tuberosity.",
    "bloodSupply": "Anterior and posterior circumflex humeral arteries, nutrient artery of the humerus and branches of the brachial artery.",
    "nerveSupply": "Closely related to the axillary nerve at the surgical neck and the radial nerve in the radial groove. Median and ulnar nerves are related to the distal humerus.",
    "ossification": "Primary ossification begins in the shaft during fetal life. Secondary ossification centers develop in the head, greater tubercle, lesser tubercle and distal end before fusing.",
    "clinical": "Fracture of the surgical neck may injure the axillary nerve. Mid-shaft fractures may damage the radial nerve causing wrist drop. Supracondylar fractures are common in children."
  },
